  <h1>Editorial Team and Standards</h1>
  <p><em>Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>This page identifies the people responsible for the content on productliabilitycalc.com and explains how the calculator and the guides are produced, reviewed, and revised. We publish this information because reliance on legal and damages content is only sensible when the reader can see who wrote it and what process produced it.</p>

  <h2>Editor-in-Chief</h2>

  <h3>Auden Cordell (AC), Product Liability Practice Lead</h3>

  <p>Auden is a paralegal with a focused practice in product liability litigation. Her work has supported attorneys on the plaintiff side of consumer-product, pharmaceutical, and motor-vehicle component cases, including coordination of multi-district litigation document review, deposition preparation, and damages-model development with consulting economists. She has spent significant time on three case categories that drive the bulk of modern product liability practice: defective auto components (airbag inflators, ignition switches, defective tires), pharmaceuticals subject to FDA Class I recalls, and consumer lithium-battery fires. She reviews every page on this site for legal accuracy and edits the methodology underlying the calculator's multipliers.</p>

  <p>Auden's editorial standards: every cited statute is checked against the controlling state code in its current version; every settlement range cited is grounded in publicly available verdict data, not memory or anecdote; and every guide is written for a layperson who has just been injured or whose family member has been injured. Industry jargon (strict liability, statute of repose, MDL, ALI Restatement) is defined in plain language on first appearance.</p>

  <h2>Contributor</h2>

  <h3>Holland Devlin (HD), Recall and Consumer Safety Reference</h3>

  <p>Holland is a paralegal who has worked in consumer-protection practice, with concentrations in CPSC and FDA recall response, false-advertising consumer-fraud claims, and class-action notice administration. She brings the regulatory side of product liability to the editorial team: understanding when a product becomes the subject of a Consumer Product Safety Commission recall, how an FDA Class I or Class II recall affects litigation posture, how an NHTSA recall is initiated and proven up, and how state attorney-general consumer-fraud actions interact with private litigation. Holland is the primary author of the case-types page and contributes the recall and regulatory references in the guides.</p>

  <h2>Editorial standards</h2>

  <h3>Independence</h3>
  <p>Neither editor represents readers of this site. Reading content here does not create an attorney-client relationship; the contributors are not licensed attorneys. We do not accept payment, consideration, or referral fees from any law firm, manufacturer, or insurance carrier to influence content. The site is supported by advertising (Google AdSense); ad placements are managed independently from editorial decisions and do not affect what is written about any product, company, or case.</p>

  <h3>Accuracy</h3>
  <p>Every claim of law on this site is sourced to a controlling statute, regulation, restatement, or appellate decision. Every settlement range cited reflects publicly available verdict data. Every recall reference is linked to the controlling agency record where one exists. When we make a generalization ("most states allow strict liability for design defects"), we acknowledge it as a generalization and note the variations.</p>

  <h3>Update cadence</h3>
  <p>The calculator's multipliers and base ranges are reviewed annually. State-by-state damages-cap data is reviewed when a state legislature passes a change or an appellate court strikes down a cap. Guides are reviewed annually as a baseline and updated immediately when a major recall, MDL settlement, or appellate ruling materially changes the practice landscape. Every page shows the most recent meaningful review date.</p>

  <h3>Corrections</h3>
  <p>We correct errors. When a correction is made, the change and the date appear in a note on the affected page. If a correction is material (e.g., a misstated statute of limitations), we also note it on the home page. Send corrections to <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a> with the page URL and the specific claim that needs review.</p>

  <h3>No predictions, no guarantees</h3>
  <p>The calculator produces an estimated range. We do not predict the outcome of any specific case, and we do not guarantee that any reader's case will fall within the estimated range. Product liability outcomes depend on liability strength, defendant insurance, jurisdictional law, and case-specific facts that no general tool can capture.</p>

  <h3>Plain language</h3>
  <p>Every page is written for a reader who is not a lawyer. Industry terms are defined the first time they appear on a page. If a reader has to consult a glossary to follow a guide, the guide has been written badly and we revise it.</p>

  <h2>How to reach the editorial team</h2>

  <p>For editorial questions, corrections, or licensing inquiries: <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a>. We typically respond within two business days.</p>

  <p>For an overview of the calculator's underlying logic, see <a href="/methodology">methodology</a>. For the case types we cover, see <a href="/case-types">case types</a>. For background on the site itself, see <a href="/about">about</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
